    </stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcsection id="s05005s" division="truck" formnum="CTS-5023S" date="03/08/1996">
        <title>POWER STEERING PUMP: VICKERS (LUK) V10NF AND V20NF</title>
        <apply>
            <configure>
                <vendorgroup/>

                <vendor>Vickers</vendor>
                <vendcodegroup/>

                <vendcode>V10NF</vendcode>
                <vendcode>V20NF</vendcode>
            </configure>
        </apply>
        <description>
            <geninfo>
                <para>V10 and V20 series pumps produce hydraulic fluid flow for operating the power steering system. The
                    V10 and V20 series pumps consist principally of:
                </para>
                <para>Refer to
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0500501">Figure 1</hotlnk>
                    for all Items in parentheses.
                </para>
                <figure id="f0500501" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0500501" filename="../figg05/G0500501.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="272px" resolution="72"/>
                    <caption>Figure 1. V10/V20 Series Pump Components</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. OUTLET PORT</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. PUMPING CARTRIDGE
                            <callout2>A. ROTOR</callout2>
                            <callout2>B. VANE</callout2>
                            <callout2>C. CAM RING</callout2>
                        </callout1>
                        <callout1>3. INLET PORT</callout1>
                        <callout1>4. SEAL</callout1>
                        <callout1>5. DRIVE SHAFT</callout1>
                        <callout1>6. BEARING</callout1>
                        <callout1>7. BODY</callout1>
                        <callout1>8. SPRING</callout1>
                        <callout1>9. PRESSURE PLATE</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
                <seqlist style="arabic">
                    <item>
                        <para>A ported body (Item 7).</para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>A drive shaft (Item 5) supported by ball bearings (Item 6).</para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>A pumping cartridge (Item 2). Pumping cartridge consists of:</para>
                        <seqlist style="alphauc">
                            <item>
                                <para>A slotted rotor (Item 2A), splined to the drive shaft.</para>
                            </item>
                            <item>
                                <para>Twelve vanes (Item 2B) fitted to the rotor slots.</para>
                            </item>
                            <item>
                                <para>An elliptical cam ring (Item 2C).</para>
                            </item>
                        </seqlist>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>A pressure plate (Item 9).</para>
                    </item>
                </seqlist>
                <para>The pumping cartridge cam ring (Item 2C) is sandwiched between the body and the cover. A ball
                    bearing and bushing located in the body and pressure plate, respectively, support each end of the
                    drive shaft and center the rotor within the cam ring.
                </para>
                <para>As the rotor is driven by the drive shaft, the vanes generate fluid flow by carrying fluid around
                    the elliptical ring contour. Fluid enters the cartridge through the inlet port in the body and is
                    discharged through the pressure plate to the outlet port in the cover.
                </para>
                <para>The pump cover houses the integral Flow Control and Relief Valve. These valves limit the fluid
                    flow in the system to a maximum prescribed rate and prevent excessive pressure build-up. Fluid not
                    required in the system is recirculated back to the tank.
                </para>
            </geninfo>
        </description>
